  "prompt": "Can God make a boulder so heavy he can't lift it?",
  "response": "The question \"Can God make a boulder so heavy He can't lift it?\" is a classic paradox often used to explore the nature of omnipotence (the idea of unlimited power). It\u2019s a variation of the *omnipotence paradox*, which challenges the logic of what it means to be all-powerful.\n\nHere\u2019s how it\u2019s typically analyzed:\n\n1. **If God can create such a boulder**, then there is something He cannot do (lift the boulder). This seems to imply that His power has limits.\n2. **If God cannot create such a boulder**, then there is also something He cannot do (create the boulder). This also seems to imply a limitation.\n\nThis paradox highlights the difficulty in defining omnipotence in terms of logical absolutes. Most theologians and philosophers address it by refining the concept of omnipotence:\n\n- **Omnipotence doesn\u2019t include logical contradictions**: The paradox involves a logical inconsistency (creating a boulder that cannot be lifted inherently defies logic). Therefore, it\u2019s not a meaningful limitation on God\u2019s power because logical contradictions are not considered \"things\" that can be done.\n- **Omnipotence is about power, not absurdity**: Being all-powerful means God can do anything that is possible, not that He can do the logically impossible, such as creating a square circle or a married bachelor.\n\nIn summary, the paradox is more of a thought experiment than a theological or philosophical problem. It challenges us to think carefully about the nature of power, logic, and divine attributes. The common resolution is that God\u2019s omnipotence does not extend to performing logical contradictions, because they are incoherent concepts rather than expressions of power.",
